<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-09-02T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-09-02T10:00:00-05:00" n="206" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d206">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/1326:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-02T18:00:00+03:00">September 2, 1934—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received September 2—5:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>282. The Japanese Embassy here insists that the Russians have reopened
                            negotiations for the sale of the Chinese Eastern Railroad and that
                            Soviet reports of Japanese threats to seize the railroad are groundless
                            and designed to arouse sympathy in the United States.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>